\begin_layout Standard
We are interested in estimating responses of the 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 model variables to structural shock 
\begin_inset Formula $j,h$
\end_inset

 periods ahead 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\theta_{j,h}=\Phi_{h}B_{0}^{-1}e_{j},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{j}$
\end_inset

 denotes the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{\text{th}}$
\end_inset

 column of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{K}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}^{-1}e_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{\text{th}}$
\end_inset

 column of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{h}$
\end_inset

 refers to the 
\begin_inset Formula $K\times K$
\end_inset

 matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

-step ahead reduced-form impulse responses.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}^{-1}e_{j}=\theta_{j,0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j,h}=\Phi_{h}\theta_{j,0}$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, let the structural shock of interest be 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1t}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we focus on the estimation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1,h}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that there is only one external instrument, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key assumption for estimating 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1,0}$
\end_inset

 is that the external instrument 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}$
\end_inset

 is correlated with 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1t}$
\end_inset

 and uncorrelated with all other structural shocks 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbb{E}[z_{t}w_{1t}] & =a\neq0\\
\mathbb{E}[z_{t}w_{kt}] & =0\text{ for }k=2,\ldots,K.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Except for the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1t}$
\end_inset

 is unobserved, these are the standard conditions required for conventional
 IV analysis.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}=B_{0}^{-1}w_{t}$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}[z_{t}u_{t}]=\mathbb{E}[B_{0}^{-1}z_{t}w_{t}]=a\theta_{1,0}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can impose the normalization that the 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,1)$
\end_inset

 element of the structural impact multiplier matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is unity.
 Under this normalization, the scalar structural parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $K\times1$
\end_inset

 vector of structural responses 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1,0}=B_{0}^{-1}e_{1}$
\end_inset

 are identified by the moment condition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}[z_{t}u_{t}]=a\theta_{1,0}
\]

\end_inset

 or, equivalently, by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}[z_{t}(y_{t}-A_{1}y_{t-1}-\cdots-A_{p}y_{t-p})-a\theta_{1,0}]=0.
\]

\end_inset

In addition, the VAR slope parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\alpha}=vec(A_{1},\ldots,A_{p})$
\end_inset

 satisfy the moment conditions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}\left[\left(y_{t-1}^{\prime},\ldots,y_{t-p}^{\prime}\right)^{\prime}\otimes\left(y_{t}-A_{1}y_{t-1}-\cdots-A_{p}y_{t-p}\right)\right]=0.
\]

\end_inset

The GMM estimator corresponding to these two sets of moment conditions is
 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\alpha}} & =\left[\left(\frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}Y_{t-1}Y_{t-1}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}\otimes I_{pK}\right]\frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\left(Y_{t-1}\otimes y_{t}\right),\\
\widehat{a} & =\frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}z_{t}\widehat{u}_{1t},\\
\widehat{\theta}_{1,0} & =\frac{1}{\widehat{a}}\frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}z_{t}\widehat{u}_{t},
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t-1}:=\left(y_{t-1}^{\prime},\ldots,y_{t-p}^{\prime}\right)^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{u}_{t}=y_{t}-\left(Y_{t-1}^{\prime}\otimes I_{pK}\right)\widehat{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}$
\end_inset

, such that the 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector of structural responses to shock 1 at horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{\theta}_{1,h}=\widehat{\Phi}_{h}\widehat{\theta}_{1,0},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\Phi}_{h}$
\end_inset

 is obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}$
\end_inset

 in the usual way for any VAR.
 The estimator is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{T}$
\end_inset

-consistent and asymptotically normal.
\end_layout

